We know this is wrong, but by the time you can explain it to them, they yawn, their eyes glaze over, and they go back to the love lives of the stars (General attention span of plankton).<br>
&quot;Everybody knows&quot; that Mars is &quot;the next step&quot;, so it's just easier to get public support for it.<br>
 Besides, there may have been life at Mars. That's the clincher in generating interest.<br>
 I like <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.spacefuture.com/archive/the_deimos_water_company.shtml">Mars' moons</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (Phobos = Fear, Diemos = Terror; the warhorses which pulled Mars' war chariot. Called Ph&amp;D by Brian O'Leary). They offer everything our Moon does, plus lots of water &amp; chemicals which could be easily brought back to Earth space.<br>
<br>
 The <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.neofuel.com">water &amp; chemicals</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> are another nail in the coffin of a Moon base: For every ton of finished goods from Moon ores, you need 7-10 times the mass in chemicals, and you can't get them on the Moon nearly as easily as at an NEA or Ph&amp;D.<br>
Really, NEAs or Ph&amp;D eliminate any big presence on the Moon; Near term, you need the volatile chemicals to be delivered to the Moon before you can do anything. Long term, if you can bring these volatiles to Earth/Moon orbit (from NEAs or Ph&amp;D), you've got <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">far</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> better resources than on the Moon, in a better position (Space, where energy is free, you have any gravity you want, and less rocketry is needed to get there &amp; back)<br>
 The Moon is called the slagpile of the solar system, because the best Lunar ores are about what an asteroid miner would throw out as not economical to process further.<br>
 It's silly to say that Lunar industry &amp; power beams could out-compete space industry &amp; asteroid mines. Similar for a big near term Martian base; too many handicaps on the surface of a big body, compared to space around a nice tasty cometary body like an NEA or Ph&amp;D)<br>
<br>
 Go to Mars because it's sexy. Divert to Ph&amp;D because they let a Mars mission pay off quickly and get big, safe, and robust fast compared to landing on Mars right away. Fear &amp; Terror will give you space.<br>
<br>
I would have picked &quot;other&quot;, and voted for an NEA, but there's even less interest in that than our Moon. Going to Mars lets you put effort into Ph&amp;D. It supports Mars exploration and everything else you want to do in space.<br>
