<br>
And unless we get REAL unlucky and find life on the first trip, or if we do the eco-terrorists with power &quot;quaranteen&quot; Mars, it will probobly take more than one trip to be pretty sure. Hopefully this, combined with resurgent public interest, will prevent flags/footprint syndrome from setting in.<br>
<br>
Now, rockets etc are extremely complex vehicles that are put through the most unholy conditions and that at the lowest practical mass etc. There is a simple rule that should guide the design of a Mars mission, and that is that there is a probability somthing vital will fail and the crew will die. What makes a safe mission different from an unsafe one is that this risk is acceptably low given the mission life of the system(s). <br>
<br>
There is a very easy way to decrease the risk of a serious failure, and that is to keep the missions as short as possible. A three-month flight out, a two/three month stay on the Mars surface, and high-tail it back home in another three-four. The more we learn about how the first trip went, then we can improve the margins of safety for longer ones later. <br>
<br>
And when I say &quot;system,&quot; I am referring to everything, including the health of the crew in low gravity as well as damage done by Martian environment to the base, etc. Mir/ISS have shown that you really really don't want to spend more than five or six months in zero-G, so that should be a maximum for each leg. <br>
<br>
Adding complexity to the system early on when it isn't needed will increase the chance of system failure, so we should absolutely use bimodal NTR and a nuclear power plant down on Mars and not risk spinning the ship. Also, to keep mission complexity to a minimum, don't rely or even not bother going to Phobos/Deimos on the first trip or three, what if they DON'T have water, or you bump into them?<br>
<br>
I also have something to say about NEAs and Lunar mining... that the technology involved for any real mining operation on these will just not be able to make any real benefical impact because of the trouble of getting it back to Earth or down to Moon/Mars. You are really going to aim an asteroid cannon at Earth? So if you can't get it back to Earth's surface, and since it will be a billion times easier to build ships on Earth (in sections even) for the forseeable remainder of our lives, that we not bother with mining base materials in space for now. <br>
